I think dropping the `invalid_reason = None` and using `if ... elif .. else` is cleaner here

```python
if highest_p_join >= self.alpha_merge:
  split.invalid_reason = InvalidSplitReason.ALPHA_MERGE
elif any( sum(node_v.values()) < self.min_child_node_size for node_v in freq.values() ):
  split.invalid_reason = InvalidSplitReason.MIN_CHILD_NODE_SIZE
elif sufficient_split and len(freq.values()) > 1:
  # Merge loop here
```

@tobes We ought to consider if we want our indexes to be zero-based or not.

We want `1, 2, 3...` for placeholders and for color thresholds.
For conditionals, this looks clean since we want to print 1 thing.

@cyrinux, is this format correct? I recall this starts off at `1` so should this be `index<2`?

In general I like to prevent naked exceptions. I imagine you're looking to catch an `AttributeError` when the `subject` doesn't exist on `self.trigger_summary_data`. Could this be simplified to 

```
def has_subject(self):
    return hasattr(this.trigger_summary_data, "subject")
```

E.g. try to create elasticsearch indices from test_indices.json file:
```json
{
  "indices": {
    "index_title": {
      "description": "Test indexing title",
      "stemming_language": "it",
      "pre_index_actions": [
        "remove_stopwords"
      ],
      "field": "title",
      "native": {
        "tokenizer": "BibIndexAuthorCountTokenizer"
      }
    },
    "index_author": {
      "description": "Test indexing author",
      "stemming_language": "it",
      "pre_index_actions": [
        "remove_stopwords"
      ],
      "field": "title",
      "elasticsearch": {
        "analyzer": "myanalyzer"
      }
    }
  },
  "virtual_indices": {
    "virtual_index_all": {
      "description": "Test virtual indexing author and title",
      "indices": ["index_title", "index_author"],
      "namespace": "records"
    },
    "virtual_index_title": {
      "description": "Test virtual indexing title",
      "indices": ["index_title"],
      "namespace": "documents"
    },
    "index_author": {
      "description": "Test virtual indexing author",
      "indices": ["index_author"],
      "namespace": "records"
    }
  }
}
```

Then, from console:
`inveniomanage indexer create elasticsearch -f "test_indices.json"`
The `load_configuration()` functions return the `IndexerConfiguration` object.
(p.s. For now, I only implemented the `.json` importer, but we can think about also implement `.cfg.` importer and `.yml` importer... XD)

@marioskogias @jirikuncar

What's wrong with `image_annotator_pb2.ImageSource(gcs_image_uri=image.source)`? If you want to be really fancy you could do this all in the return statement:

```python
return image_annotator_pb2.Image(
    source=image_annotator_pb2.ImageSource(
        gcs_image_uri=image.source,
    ),
)
```

Re `is_0x_prefixed`.  Lets only support text typed values and explicitely raise if the value is not a text type.

```
def is_0x_prefixed(value):
    if not is_text(value):
        raise TypeError("is_0x_prefixed requires text typed arguments.  Got: {0}".format(type(value)))
    return is_prefixed(value, '0x') or is_prefixed(value, '0X')
```

AFAIR pip (setuptools?) doesn't support this kind of notation in `install_requires` (at least in certain range of versions).
I'd say it's better to go for extras-based syntax:
```python
extra_requires = {
    ':python_version<"3.7"': [
        'idna-ssl>=1.0',
    ],
}
```

